[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

Bluetongue virus (BTV) (Reoviridae: Orbivirus) is a vector-borne pathogen that causes hemorrhagic disease (HD) in ruminants, mainly sheep, and less frequently goats, buffalo, deer, antelopes and camels.
In South America, viral isolations from field samples have only been reported in Argentina, Brazil and Guyana. Serologic evidence has been reported in Chile, Perú, Ecuador, Colombia, Venezuela, Suriname and French Guyana.

In Brazil, BTV was first described in São Paulo in 1978. After that, several reports have shown that the virus is widespread all over Brazil. Serologic data can be found in the whole country, although the virus was isolated only in 2 opportunities: in 1980, BTV4 was isolated in Florida (USA) from Brazilian zebu cattle which had been quarantined; and in 2001, BTV12 was isolated from sheep showing clinical signs of bluetongue.

The few surveys that examined seroprevalence in cervids from South America failed to find a positive result. The only previous report on BTV infecting a South American deer was published this year [2016] in another _Mazama nana_ kept in captivity from the same zoo (see ProMED post # 20160119.3948490). - Mod.PMB]
